In the past, in order to cancel a command that we have bound to a joystick button, we updated a variable in the subsystem the command uses, and inside the isFinished of the command we check if the subsystem is telling the command to stop.

Example (pseudo code) of RobotContainer controller.x.onTrue() = new AlignGamepiece(VisionSubsystem) – Command we want to cancel controller.b.onTrue() = new SetCancelAlign(VisionSubsystem, true) – Calls setCancel(true) in order to cancel AlignGamepiece

Then inside the VisionSubsystem: void setCancel(boolean value) { this.requestCancel = value} boolean getCancel() {return this.requestCancel}

Finally inside the AlignGamepiece command we would have: isFinished() { return this.visionSubsystem.getCancel() }

This works fine, but is extremely hard to integrate inside a parallel or sequential command group, as every command needs to take in the same cancel method from the subsystem. There must be a better way of doing this that we have overlooked. Any advice would be appreciated.

accepted_answer.excerpt:
Don’t do this. end is a lifecycle function meant to be called a) in a specific order and b) exclusively by the command scheduler. 
To the OP: 
Commands can be cancelled manually by calling command.cancel(), which will tell the scheduler to cancel the command (and run the appropriate lifecycle method&hellip;
